bout the changing global order, a global perspective is necessary. This book explores how the concept of a multipolar order is being used for different purposes in different national contexts. From rising powers to established powers, contemporary debates are analysed by a set of leading scholars to provide in-depth insight into the use and abuse of a widely employed but rarely explored concept.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBalance of power. 0aGlobalization. 0aWorld politicsy21st century. 0aWorld politics. 4aPolitical Studies 2022. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aChinese foreign policy.  aIndian foreign policy.  aUnited States foreign policy.  aglobal order.  agreat powers.  ainternational relations.  amultipolarity.  apolarity.  apower transition.  asuperpowers.1 aBlagden, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChebankova, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnvall, H. D. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhoo, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQingmin, Zhang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchenoni, Luis L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZala, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZala, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615938040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/